Task 1: Control Services with systemctl
Subtask 1.1: Understanding Systemd Basics
First, let's explore the systemd environment and understand its structure.

Step 1: Check systemd version and status

systemctl --version
Step 2: View system state

systemctl status
Step 3: List all available services

systemctl list-units --type=service
Step 4: List all service unit files

systemctl list-unit-files --type=service
Subtask 1.2: Basic Service Control Operations
Step 1: Check the status of a common service (SSH)

systemctl status ssh
If SSH service is not available, use another common service:

systemctl status cron
Step 2: Stop a service

sudo systemctl stop cron
Step 3: Verify the service is stopped

systemctl status cron
Step 4: Start the service again

sudo systemctl start cron
Step 5: Restart a service

sudo systemctl restart cron
Step 6: Reload service configuration without stopping

sudo systemctl reload cron
Subtask 1.3: Service Enable/Disable Operations
Step 1: Check if a service is enabled to start at boot

systemctl is-enabled cron
Step 2: Disable a service from starting at boot

sudo systemctl disable cron
Step 3: Verify the service is disabled

systemctl is-enabled cron
Step 4: Enable the service to start at boot

sudo systemctl enable cron
Step 5: Enable and start a service simultaneously

sudo systemctl enable --now cron
Subtask 1.4: Advanced Service Management
Step 1: Mask a service (prevent it from being started)

sudo systemctl mask cron
Step 2: Try to start the masked service

sudo systemctl start cron
Step 3: Unmask the service

sudo systemctl unmask cron
Step 4: View service dependencies

systemctl list-dependencies cron
Task 2: Create Custom Systemd Service Units
Subtask 2.1: Create a Simple Custom Service
Step 1: Create a simple script that our service will run

sudo mkdir -p /opt/myapp
Step 2: Create the application script

sudo nano /opt/myapp/myservice.sh
Add the following content:

#!/bin/bash
# Simple service script
LOG_FILE="/var/log/myservice.log"

while true; do
    echo "$(date): MyService is running - PID: $$" >> $LOG_FILE
    sleep 30
done
Step 3: Make the script executable

sudo chmod +x /opt/myapp/myservice.sh
Step 4: Test the script manually

sudo /opt/myapp/myservice.sh &
Step 5: Stop the test process

sudo pkill -f myservice.sh
Subtask 2.2: Create the Systemd Service Unit File
Step 1: Create the service unit file

sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/myservice.service
Step 2: Add the following service configuration

[Unit]
Description=My Custom Service
Documentation=https://example.com/myservice
After=network.target
Wants=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
User=root
Group=root
ExecStart=/opt/myapp/myservice.sh
ExecReload=/bin/kill -HUP $MAINPID
Restart=always
RestartSec=10
StandardOutput=journal
StandardError=journal

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
Step 3: Reload systemd to recognize the new service

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
Step 4: Check the service status

systemctl status myservice
Subtask 2.3: Test the Custom Service
Step 1: Start the custom service

sudo systemctl start myservice
Step 2: Check service status

systemctl status myservice
Step 3: Enable the service for automatic startup

sudo systemctl enable myservice
Step 4: Verify the service is running and logging

tail -f /var/log/myservice.log
Press Ctrl+C to stop viewing the log.

Subtask 2.4: Create an Advanced Service with Environment Variables
Step 1: Create an advanced service script

sudo nano /opt/myapp/advanced-service.sh
Add the following content:

#!/bin/bash
# Advanced service script with environment variables

LOG_FILE="${LOG_PATH:-/var/log/advanced-service.log}"
SERVICE_NAME="${SERVICE_NAME:-AdvancedService}"
INTERVAL="${SLEEP_INTERVAL:-15}"

echo "Starting $SERVICE_NAME with interval $INTERVAL seconds" >> $LOG_FILE

while true; do
    echo "$(date): $SERVICE_NAME is active - Environment: $ENVIRONMENT" >> $LOG_FILE
    sleep $INTERVAL
done
Step 2: Make the script executable

sudo chmod +x /opt/myapp/advanced-service.sh
Step 3: Create environment file

sudo nano /etc/default/advanced-service
Add the following content:

# Environment variables for advanced-service
SERVICE_NAME=ProductionService
ENVIRONMENT=Production
LOG_PATH=/var/log/advanced-service.log
SLEEP_INTERVAL=20
Step 4: Create the advanced service unit file

sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/advanced-service.service
Add the following configuration:

[Unit]
Description=Advanced Custom Service
Documentation=https://example.com/advanced-service
After=network.target multi-user.target
Requires=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
User=root
Group=root
EnvironmentFile=/etc/default/advanced-service
ExecStart=/opt/myapp/advanced-service.sh
ExecStop=/bin/kill -TERM $MAINPID
ExecReload=/bin/kill -HUP $MAINPID
Restart=on-failure
RestartSec=5
TimeoutStartSec=30
TimeoutStopSec=30
StandardOutput=journal
StandardError=journal

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
Step 5: Reload systemd and start the advanced service

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl start advanced-service
sudo systemctl enable advanced-service
Step 6: Verify the advanced service

systemctl status advanced-service
tail /var/log/advanced-service.log
Task 3: Use journalctl to Monitor Service Logs
Subtask 3.1: Basic journalctl Operations
Step 1: View all journal entries

sudo journalctl
Press q to quit the viewer.

Step 2: View journal entries for a specific service

sudo journalctl -u myservice
Step 3: View journal entries in real-time (follow mode)

sudo journalctl -u myservice -f
Press Ctrl+C to stop following.

Step 4: View journal entries for the current boot

sudo journalctl -b
Step 5: View journal entries for a specific time range

sudo journalctl --since "1 hour ago"
Subtask 3.2: Advanced journalctl Filtering
Step 1: View logs with specific priority levels

sudo journalctl -p err
Step 2: View logs for multiple services

sudo journalctl -u myservice -u advanced-service
Step 3: View logs in JSON format

sudo journalctl -u myservice -o json-pretty
Step 4: View logs with timestamps

sudo journalctl -u myservice --since "10 minutes ago" --until "5 minutes ago"
Step 5: View kernel messages

sudo journalctl -k
Subtask 3.3: Service-Specific Log Analysis
Step 1: Check service startup logs

sudo journalctl -u myservice --since "today" | grep -i start
Step 2: Monitor service failures

sudo journalctl -u myservice -p err --since "today"
Step 3: View service logs with line numbers

sudo journalctl -u myservice -n 50
Step 4: Export logs to a file

sudo journalctl -u myservice --since "1 hour ago" > /tmp/myservice-logs.txt
Step 5: View the exported logs

cat /tmp/myservice-logs.txt
Subtask 3.4: Journal Configuration and Maintenance
Step 1: Check journal disk usage

sudo journalctl --disk-usage
Step 2: View journal configuration

sudo systemctl status systemd-journald
Step 3: Rotate journal files

sudo systemctl kill --kill-who=main --signal=SIGUSR2 systemd-journald
Step 4: Clean old journal entries

sudo journalctl --vacuum-time=7d
Step 5: Verify journal integrity

sudo journalctl --verify
Practical Exercise: Service Troubleshooting
Exercise 1: Troubleshoot a Failing Service
Step 1: Create a problematic service script

sudo nano /opt/myapp/problem-service.sh
Add the following content:

#!/bin/bash
# Problematic service script
echo "Starting problematic service"
sleep 5
exit 1  # This will cause the service to fail
Step 2: Make it executable

sudo chmod +x /opt/myapp/problem-service.sh
Step 3: Create service unit file

sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/problem-service.service
Add the following content:

[Unit]
Description=Problem Service for Troubleshooting
After=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
ExecStart=/opt/myapp/problem-service.sh
Restart=on-failure
RestartSec=10

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
Step 4: Reload and start the service

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl start problem-service
Step 5: Check service status

systemctl status problem-service
Step 6: Analyze the failure using journalctl

sudo journalctl -u problem-service -n 20
Step 7: Fix the service by modifying the script

sudo nano /opt/myapp/problem-service.sh
Change the content to:

#!/bin/bash
# Fixed service script
LOG_FILE="/var/log/problem-service.log"

echo "$(date): Problem service started successfully" >> $LOG_FILE

while true; do
    echo "$(date): Service running normally" >> $LOG_FILE
    sleep 60
done
Step 8: Restart the service and verify it works

sudo systemctl restart problem-service
systemctl status problem-service
tail /var/log/problem-service.log
Service Management Best Practices
Security Considerations
Step 1: Create a dedicated user for services

sudo useradd -r -s /bin/false myservice-user
Step 2: Update service to run as non-root user

sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/myservice.service
Modify the [Service] section:

[Service]
Type=simple
User=myservice-user
Group=myservice-user
ExecStart=/opt/myapp/myservice.sh
Step 3: Adjust file permissions

sudo chown myservice-user:myservice-user /opt/myapp/myservice.sh
sudo touch /var/log/myservice.log
sudo chown myservice-user:myservice-user /var/log/myservice.log
Step 4: Reload and restart the service

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl restart myservice
systemctl status myservice
Verification and Testing
Final Verification Steps
Step 1: List all custom services created

systemctl list-unit-files | grep -E "(myservice|advanced-service|problem-service)"
Step 2: Check status of all custom services

systemctl status myservice advanced-service problem-service
Step 3: Verify services start automatically after reboot simulation

sudo systemctl reboot
After the system restarts, check:

